{"type":"message","id":"746abd96","parentId":"8bb537d2","timestamp":"2026-05-15T13:00:55.370Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the information I need. Let me understand the setup:\n\n1. **How evolver works**: It's designed to be run as a background loop (`node index.js --loop`) that monitors session logs and triggers evolution cycles when signals are detected.\n\n2. **Cron approach**: I can set up a cron job to periodically run `node index.js` to check for signals and run evolution cycles.\n\n3. **The core problem**: When evolver ran before, it triggered a massive innovation attempt (155 files changed) because it misread the signals from the session. The signal parsing picked up content from the dream journal (`user_feature_request:给自己取个名字...`) combined with tool usage patterns, which led it to choose an overly aggressive innovation gene.\n   \nThe real issue is that evolver's session signal detection is interpreting the conversation context too broadly. I need to constrain its behavior by setting stricter limits on how many files it can modify per cycle, which I can do through the config file.\n\nBeyond that, I should establish a cron schedule to run evolver at regular intervals—probably every hour or couple of hours rather than constantly in the background. I'll also need to set the evolution strategy to `harden` for safer, lower-risk mutations, adjust the file and line count thresholds, and create an `.env` file to tie everything together.\n","thinkingSignature":"a310348398122b279c7a5bf9a57b3094acfdc9215f50d95cdd87e85430346f96"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n现在我清楚整体架构了。让我做这几件事：\n\n1. 设置 `.env` 配置（限制改动范围 + 策略调整）\n2. 创建 cron 定时触发\n3. 修复 signal 检测的误判问题\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_elmnel3za4g6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/capability-evolver/src/config.js 2>/dev/null | grep -E \"HARD_CAP|max_files|BLAST|forbidden|FILES\" | head -20"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ca