{"type":"message","id":"7560ef16","parentId":"a9f75aae","timestamp":"2026-05-15T13:12:03.032Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The signal is still there even after trimming the memory_graph. The signal must be coming from a session log or the session corpus. Let me check - we renamed the session corpus files. But there must still be more sources of this signal.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully - the evolver is picking up these signals from recent session logs, not just from memory_graph. The \"给我自己取个名字\" is coming from the session transcripts that memory-core is generating dreams from.\n\nThe key issue is that evolver keeps seeing the same stuck signals because:\n1. The session logs still contain the problematic conversation\n2. The memory-graph keeps recording the same signal patterns\n\nFor the cron job, since it uses `EVOLVE_STRATEGY=harden` and the cron message filters out the bad signals, I think it should be fine. \n\nBut I need to trace where these repeated signals are actually originating from - they're persisting even after I cleared the memory_graph. The session logs in `~/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/` might be the culprit, since they contain that same \"给自己取个名字\" conversation in their transcripts.\n\nWait, I'm realizing evolver might be reading directly from the OpenClaw session archives themselves. Since it has access to the main session logs through the workspace path, it's pulling signal data from there rather than just from the memory graph I cleared. The session-scoped evolution directory in `memory/evolution/scopes/` is likely where it's finding these persistent signals. I should set up the cron job to handle this properly since the evolver is still producing the same stuck signals from multiple sources. The cron agent uses `--session isolated`, so it won't have access to the main session's transcript - it will only see the isolated session context with the message prompt. Since the bad signals are coming from the main session's transcript history, and the isolated cron session doesn't have that context, it shouldn't trigger the same stuck behavior. The agent will run evolver with a clean context, which should let it produce legitimate output instead of getting stuck on those bad signals.\n\nLet me just report the current status to the user: the cron job is set up to run daily at 9 AM, but evolver is stuck on some bad signals from the main session that keep producing the same failed output. I'm waiting to see if the cron job actually fixes this when it runs.\n","thinkingSignature":"cfb452a12cc3388cf2469197b22476d96bd7c5555d86e63cce4a39ff61be1c56"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3pvz9b6b0u5p_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 验证 cron 已设置\nopenclaw cron list 2>&1 | grep -E \"Name|capability|evolver\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":848,"output":534,"cacheRead":143616,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":144998,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778850699710,"responseId":"06564e8c85b958f0eb2d1919296ae5e7"}}
