{"type":"message","id":"1dbff278","parentId":"38187551","timestamp":"2026-05-15T13:22:04.800Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The version on the hub is v1.27.3, and the installed one is v1.67.4. The one in the workspace is actually much newer (v1.67.4). But the hub page shows v1.27.3. Wait, that seems backwards - v1.67.4 > v1.27.3, so the installed one is newer.\n\nActually wait - `@evomap/evolver` version 1.67.4 and the hub shows 1.27.3. The installed one is newer. But it's from the original EvoMap project, not the CocoLoop fork.\n \nThe skill description claims \"OpenClaw 官方维护\" but it's actually just EvoMap's original evolver project - the user was right to call this out as essentially Hermes/EvoMap copied over. The hub page is misleading about who actually maintains it.\n\nLooking at the \"零依赖\" claim, it's technically true for runtime but the package.json shows 25+ devDependencies that get installed anyway. The real gaps are that the skill is generic not OpenClaw-specific, doesn't integrate properly with multi-agent workspaces, and uses an overly broad signal detection system - all problems the user correctly identified.\n\nI should focus my response on the version differences (v1.67.4 installed versus v1.27.3 on hub) and address why it's not working well for OpenClaw's actual use case rather than debating whether it's a copy of Hermes.\n","thinkingSignature":"513ebd7c560fe64816f1354f36420e171287f325685e65c52a0400460f98efa0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_j7imwezrb293_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 检查你装的版本 vs hub 上的版本\necho \"=== 已安装版本 ===\" \ncat ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/capability-evolver/package.json | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print('name:', d.get('name')); print('version:', d.get('version'))\"\n\necho \"=== hub 显示版本 ===\"\necho \"v1.27.3\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":236,"output":417,"cacheRead":13568